</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[154,1111,621,933]" lastBlockId="33.[159,1116,173,393]" lastPageId="33" lastPageNumber="3207" pageId="32" pageNumber="3206">
<emphasis box="[194,329,685,709]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="3206">Description.</emphasis>
Shell 3.32 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[457,484,684,709]" pageId="32" pageNumber="3206">6</emphasis>
<quantity box="[483,582,685,709]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.17" pageId="32" pageNumber="3206" unit="mm" value="2.17">2.17 mm</quantity>
. Equivalve. Inequilateral, beaks close to the anterior margin. Outline elongate–subovate; anterior reduced, margin narrowly rounded; ventral and dorsal margins gently curved, oblique and subparallel; posterior broadly rounded. Small depressed lunule present. Sculpture smooth except for growth lines and faint radial striations which are most obvious under transmitted light. Hinge with prominent teeth in lv (
<figureCitation box="[739,853,845,869]" captionStart="FIGS" captionStartId="32.[159,175,1682,1704]" captionTargetBox="[157,1109,969,1646]" captionTargetId="figure-214@32.[154,1111,967,1649]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGS. 99–102. Montacutid, NMW.Z.2000.086.00014 (SEM): (99) external left valve; (100) internal left valve; (101, 102) hinge view, left and right valves." pageId="32" pageNumber="3206">figure 101</figureCitation>
), much weaker in rv (
<figureCitation box="[161,275,877,901]" captionStart="FIGS" captionStartId="32.[159,175,1682,1704]" captionTargetBox="[157,1109,969,1646]" captionTargetId="figure-214@32.[154,1111,967,1649]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGS. 99–102. Montacutid, NMW.Z.2000.086.00014 (SEM): (99) external left valve; (100) internal left valve; (101, 102) hinge view, left and right valves." pageId="32" pageNumber="3206">figure 102</figureCitation>
); small anterior tooth (at) at anterior end of lunule margin; remote posterior lateral tooth (pt) separated from beak by contiguous nymph. Internal resilium large, external ligament present on nymph. Inner margin smooth. Pallial line as a series of discontinuous scars. Shell white in colour.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="32" pageNumber="3206" startId="32.[159,175,1682,1704]" targetBox="[157,1109,969,1646]" targetPageId="32">
<paragraph blockId="32.[159,1105,1682,1730]" pageId="32" pageNumber="3206">FIGS. 99–102. Montacutid, NMW.Z.2000.086.00014 (SEM): (99) external left valve; (100) internal left valve; (101, 102) hinge view, left and right valves.</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="33.[159,1116,173,393]" pageId="33" pageNumber="3207">
<emphasis box="[199,306,238,262]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="3207">Remarks.</emphasis>
This shell is distinctive and unusual for the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W.Clark" authorityYear="1855" box="[877,1037,238,262]" class="Bivalvia" family="Montacutidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galeommatida" pageId="33" pageNumber="3207" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Montacutidae</taxonomicName>
in its strongly inequilateral outline. We have placed this shell in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W.Clark" authorityYear="1855" box="[956,1116,270,294]" class="Bivalvia" family="Montacutidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galeommatida" pageId="33" pageNumber="3207" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Montacutidae</taxonomicName>
because of the lack of true cardinal teeth and the presence of a large internal resilium. In outline it is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="A. Adams, 1864" authorityName="A. Adams" authorityYear="1864" box="[590,931,336,360]" class="Bivalvia" family="Lasaeidae" genus="Thecodonta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galeommatida" pageId="33" pageNumber="3207" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[590,720,336,360]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="3207">Thecodonta</emphasis>
A. Adams, 1864
</taxonomicName>
, but the dentitions, as given in 
<bibRefCitation author="Chavan" box="[371,543,369,393]" firstAuthor="Chavan" pageId="33" pageNumber="3207" pagination="518 - 543" refId="ref19517" refString="CHAVAN, A., 1969, Leptonacea &amp; Cyamiacea, in R. C. Moore (ed.) Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology, Part N, Vol. 2, Mollusca 6, Bivalvia (Boulder, CO: The Geological Society of America, Inc. and the University of Kansas), pp. N 518 - 543." type="book chapter" year="1969">Chavan (1969)</bibRefCitation>
, do not agree.
</paragraph>
